        "title": "How To : Add Navigation Menu Support In Wordpress Themes",
        "slug": "how-to-add-navigation-menu-support-in-wordpress-themes",
        "markdown": "\nWell its good that you started to create your own theme, and by now you must have known that WordPress is nothing without its codex still some find it rather difficult to add navigation menu support in wordpress themes\n\nIn this article we’ll learn to use the WordPress codex to register navigation menus in our wordpress theme without any plugin\n\n**Navigation Menus** build up an integral part of the theme and it is very necessary to have them in place, after you have created your list of files required to create your theme you must now start working on the codex that binds together all the essential components of the theme eg: navigation.\n\nNavigation menus are not active by default if you are creating a theme, it needs to be setup first. Don’t fret the method is pretty easy and will take just 5 minutes to set it up.\n\nYou must have by now created a file called as Functions.php in your theme that holds all the basic functions of WordPress. We’ll be working in this file.\n\nOpen up the Funtions.php file in a code editor program and paste in the following code before this closing php tag ` ?> ` in the end of the functions.php file :\n\nfunction register_my_menus() { register_nav_menus( array( 'header-menu' => __( 'Header Menu' ), 'extra-menu' => __( 'Extra Menu' ) ) ); } add_action( 'init', 'register_my_menus' );\n\n**What this code does is that, it tells WordPress to register two navigation menus :**\n\n1. Header Menu\n2. Extra Menu\n\nso that it can be called upon where ever you may require it in the theme.\n\n**Our job isn’t done yet !**\n\nNext step is to be use this function in our theme. To do this open the file header.php for demo purposes we’ll be placing it in the header section which is where our navigation exits.\n\nNow to register navigation place this code before the end of the ` < head >` tag or where ever you want to place your navigation bar.\n\n<nav> <?php wp_nav_menu( array( 'theme_location' => 'header-menu' ) ); ?> </nav> Or <nav> <?php wp_nav_menu( array( 'theme_location' => 'extra-menu' ) ); ?> </nav>\n\n**To confirm your installation goto WordPress dashboard > Appearance > Menus**** Here you’ll see :****Two navigation Locations which we created just now.**\n\n \n\n[![Add Navigation Menu Support In WordPress Themes](http://i2.wp.com/uiuxblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/wordpress-register-navigation-codextuts.png?resize=871%2C196)](http://i2.wp.com/uiuxblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/wordpress-register-navigation-codextuts.png)\n\n**Just Select the one you need and thats it.**\n\n\n",
        "html": "<p>Well its good that you started to create your own theme, and by now you must have known that WordPress is nothing without its codex still some find it rather difficult to add navigation menu support in wordpress themes</p>\n\n<p>In this article we’ll learn to use the WordPress codex to register navigation menus in our wordpress theme without any plugin</p>\n\n<p><strong>Navigation Menus</strong> build up an integral part of the theme and it is very necessary to have them in place, after you have created your list of files required to create your theme you must now start working on the codex that binds together all the essential components of the theme eg: navigation.</p>\n\n<p>Navigation menus are not active by default if you are creating a theme, it needs to be setup first. Don’t fret the method is pretty easy and will take just 5 minutes to set it up.</p>\n\n<p>You must have by now created a file called as Functions.php in your theme that holds all the basic functions of WordPress. We’ll be working in this file.</p>\n\n<p>Open up the Funtions.php file in a code editor program and paste in the following code before this closing php tag <code>?&gt;</code> in the end of the functions.php file :</p>\n\n<p>function register<em>my</em>menus() { register<em>nav</em>menus( array( 'header-menu' => <em>_( 'Header Menu' ), 'extra-menu' => _</em>( 'Extra Menu' ) ) ); } add<em>action( 'init', 'register</em>my_menus' );</p>\n\n<p><strong>What this code does is that, it tells WordPress to register two navigation menus :</strong></p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Header Menu  </li>\n<li>Extra Menu</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>so that it can be called upon where ever you may require it in the theme.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Our job isn’t done yet !</strong></p>\n\n<p>Next step is to be use this function in our theme. To do this open the file header.php for demo purposes we’ll be placing it in the header section which is where our navigation exits.</p>\n\n<p>Now to register navigation place this code before the end of the <code>&lt; head &gt;</code> tag or where ever you want to place your navigation bar.</p>\n\n<nav> <?php wp_nav_menu( array( 'theme_location' => 'header-menu' ) ); ?> </nav> Or <nav> <?php wp_nav_menu( array( 'theme_location' => 'extra-menu' ) ); ?> </nav>\n\n<p><strong>To confirm your installation goto WordPress dashboard > Appearance > Menus<em>*</strong> Here you’ll see :<strong></em>*Two navigation Locations which we created just now.</strong></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i2.wp.com/uiuxblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/wordpress-register-navigation-codextuts.png\"><img src=\"http://i2.wp.com/uiuxblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/wordpress-register-navigation-codextuts.png?resize=871%2C196\" alt=\"Add Navigation Menu Support In WordPress Themes\" title=\"\" /></a></p>\n\n<p><strong>Just Select the one you need and thats it.</strong></p>",
