        "uuid": "70e29d7a-e035-41ba-9f82-956d107c053a",
        "title": "How To : Add Featured Image Support In A Wordpress Theme",
        "slug": "how-to-add-featured-image-support-in-a-wordpress-theme",
        "markdown": "\nFeatured image as the name suggests displays a particular image related to the post you select to be the featured one, on the archives page eg: the homepage of a blog.  \n If you are creating a new theme by yourself then you’ll have to enable this feature within your theme to be able to use it.  \n In this article you’ll learn to add featured image support in a wordpress theme without use of any plugin but strictly the wordpress codex.  \n Most simple way is to register this functionality in you theme is by using functions file ie the **Functions.php **\n\nLets begin then, open up your functions.php file in a code editor and paste this in :\n\n \n\nadd_theme_support( 'post-thumbnails' );\n\nAnd thats it now when you create a new post you’ll be able to see the section where you can “set the featured image” it usually lies below the “add tags” area in the wordpress post editor section.\n\n**Anyways its a job half done,**\n\nNext step is to make our theme support this feature ie, we have to use it where we need. In this case let us consider the homepage of a blog where we have a list of all the posts.\n\nThe homepage for a theme would be the index.php file in your WordPress theme.\n\nOpen it up in the code editor and paste this in :\n\n<a href=\"<?php the_permalink() ?>\"> <?php if(has_post_thumbnail()) { ?> <?php the_post_thumbnail('medium');?> <?php } ?> </a>\n\nWhat this does is, it adds a link of the post that the image was associated to and also shows the featured image wherever you request for it.\n\n[![how-to-enable-featured-image-in-wordpress-codextuts](http://i0.wp.com/uiuxblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/how-to-enable-featured-image-in-wordpress-codextuts.png?resize=807%2C211)](http://i0.wp.com/uiuxblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/how-to-enable-featured-image-in-wordpress-codextuts.png)\n\nAs in this screenshot above, we place the code after the “Post-Title” but before the “Meta Content” followed by the excerpt and the read more link.\n\n**Follow the above steps and you’ll be able to set it up in no time.  \n Any problem ? ask them in comments.**\n\n\n",
        "html": "<p>Featured image as the name suggests displays a particular image related to the post you select to be the featured one, on the archives page eg: the homepage of a blog. <br />\n If you are creating a new theme by yourself then you’ll have to enable this feature within your theme to be able to use it. <br />\n In this article you’ll learn to add featured image support in a wordpress theme without use of any plugin but strictly the wordpress codex. <br />\n Most simple way is to register this functionality in you theme is by using functions file ie the <em>*Functions.php *</em></p>\n\n<p>Lets begin then, open up your functions.php file in a code editor and paste this in :</p>\n\n<p>add_theme_support( 'post-thumbnails' );</p>\n\n<p>And thats it now when you create a new post you’ll be able to see the section where you can “set the featured image” it usually lies below the “add tags” area in the wordpress post editor section.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Anyways its a job half done,</strong></p>\n\n<p>Next step is to make our theme support this feature ie, we have to use it where we need. In this case let us consider the homepage of a blog where we have a list of all the posts.</p>\n\n<p>The homepage for a theme would be the index.php file in your WordPress theme.</p>\n\n<p>Open it up in the code editor and paste this in :</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"<?php the_permalink() ?>\"> <?php if(has<em>post</em>thumbnail()) { ?> <?php the<em>post</em>thumbnail('medium');?> <?php } ?> </a></p>\n\n<p>What this does is, it adds a link of the post that the image was associated to and also shows the featured image wherever you request for it.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i0.wp.com/uiuxblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/how-to-enable-featured-image-in-wordpress-codextuts.png\"><img src=\"http://i0.wp.com/uiuxblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/how-to-enable-featured-image-in-wordpress-codextuts.png?resize=807%2C211\" alt=\"how-to-enable-featured-image-in-wordpress-codextuts\" title=\"\" /></a></p>\n\n<p>As in this screenshot above, we place the code after the “Post-Title” but before the “Meta Content” followed by the excerpt and the read more link.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Follow the above steps and you’ll be able to set it up in no time. <br />\n Any problem ? ask them in comments.</strong></p>",
