        "id": 16,
        "uuid": "08fce77e-cfba-4ac7-8be5-1346b37f5ccf",
        "title": "How To : Add Related Posts Support in Wordpress Theme Without Plugins",
        "slug": "how-to-add-related-posts-support-in-wordpress-theme-without-plugins",
        "markdown": "\nRelated posts display similar posts to the post type that you or the user may currently be viewing, related posts work by showing you few related posts that share same category or tag.In this article we’ll learn how to add related posts support in your wordpress theme without any plugins but by using the wordpress codex.\n\nThere are various plugins using which you can achieve this, but it is usually not recommended to use alot of plugins as they tend to slow down your web page. So why not use the one that wordpress provides us with.\n\nAs you may know the related posts are usually displayed at the end of single post, so we’ll be working in the single.php file of your wordpress theme.\n\n**Open up the single.php file in code editor and paste this in right after the end of `</article> ` tag **\n\n<div class=\"related_posts\"> <h3>Related Posts :</h3> <?php $related = get_posts( array( 'category__in' => wp_get_post_categories($post->ID), 'numberposts' => 3, 'post__not_in' => array($post->ID) ) ); if( $related ) foreach( $related as $post ) { setup_postdata($post); ?> <div class=\"rel-single\"> <a href=\"<?php the_permalink() ?>\"><?php if(has_post_thumbnail()) { ?> <?php the_post_thumbnail('medium');?> <?php } ?> </a> <a href=\"<?php the_permalink() ?>\"><?php the_title(); ?></a> </div> <?php } wp_reset_postdata(); ?> </div>\n\nAfter successful installation of this you’ll now be able to see the related posts along with thier permalink  and a featured image.  \n The posts will be displayed in form of a list, you can style it using CSS according to your needs.\n\n**Stuck somewhere ? give a shout out in comments.**\n\n\n",
        "html": "<p>Related posts display similar posts to the post type that you or the user may currently be viewing, related posts work by showing you few related posts that share same category or tag.In this article we’ll learn how to add related posts support in your wordpress theme without any plugins but by using the wordpress codex.</p>\n\n<p>There are various plugins using which you can achieve this, but it is usually not recommended to use alot of plugins as they tend to slow down your web page. So why not use the one that wordpress provides us with.</p>\n\n<p>As you may know the related posts are usually displayed at the end of single post, so we’ll be working in the single.php file of your wordpress theme.</p>\n\n<p><em>*Open up the single.php file in code editor and paste this in right after the end of <code>&lt;/article&gt;</code> tag *</em></p>\n\n<div class=\"related_posts\"> <h3>Related Posts :</h3> <?php $related = get_posts( array( 'category__in' => wp_get_post_categories($post->ID), 'numberposts' => 3, 'post__not_in' => array($post->ID) ) ); if( $related ) foreach( $related as $post ) { setup_postdata($post); ?> <div class=\"rel-single\"> <a href=\"<?php the_permalink() ?>\"><?php if(has_post_thumbnail()) { ?> <?php the_post_thumbnail('medium');?> <?php } ?> </a> <a href=\"<?php the_permalink() ?>\"><?php the_title(); ?></a> </div> <?php } wp_reset_postdata(); ?> </div>\n\n<p>After successful installation of this you’ll now be able to see the related posts along with thier permalink  and a featured image. <br />\n The posts will be displayed in form of a list, you can style it using CSS according to your needs.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Stuck somewhere ? give a shout out in comments.</strong></p>",
